===Motivation===

Taproot ([[bip-0341.mediawiki|BIP 341]]) key-path spending requires only a Schnorr signature for the output key. A quantum adversary capable of solving the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem (ECDLP) can forge Schnorr signatures and key-path spend any witness version 1 output, bypassing any post-quantum protections in the script tree.

This is particularly dangerous for outputs constructed with the NUMS internal key recommended in BIP 341. The NUMS point <code>H = lift_x(0x50929b74c1a04954b78b4b6035e97a5e078a5a0f28ec96d547bfee9ace803ac0)</code> has an unknown discrete logarithm under classical computation, but a quantum computer can recover it. An attacker could then compute the tweak, derive the private key for the output key <code>Q</code>, and key-path spend — completely bypassing the script tree that may contain post-quantum spending conditions.

This BIP closes that attack vector by requiring the internal key to be disclosed in key-path spends and banning known NUMS points.

==Design==

===Internal key disclosure via annex===

BIP 341 determines key-path vs script-path spending by witness element count: exactly 1 element (after removing the optional annex) is a key-path spend; 2+ elements is a script-path spend. Adding extra witness elements to a key-path spend would break this distinction.

The annex is the natural carrier for the internal key because it is already stripped before the key-path/script-path determination and is committed to in the Schnorr sighash. This BIP defines annex type byte <code>0x02</code> for internal key disclosure.

===NUMS point ban===

The taproot tweak construction <code>Q = P + hash(TapTweak, bytes(P) || ...) * G</code> binds the internal key <code>P</code> to the output key <code>Q</code> through a SHA-256 hash commitment. Even a quantum adversary who can solve ECDLP cannot find an alternative <code>P' != P</code> that produces the same <code>Q</code>, because this would require breaking SHA-256 preimage resistance (128-bit security under Grover's algorithm).

Therefore, requiring <code>P</code> in the witness and verifying it against the tweak formula makes the NUMS ban enforceable: the attacker cannot provide a fake <code>P != H</code> to bypass the ban.

===Bare-key spending is disabled===

====Definition====

A '''bare-key output''' is a witness version 1 (Taproot) output where the output key <code>Q</code> is a raw public key that was '''not''' constructed using the taproot tweak formula. That is, there exists no internal key <code>P</code> and optional merkle root <code>m</code> such that <code>Q = P + hash(TapTweak, bytes(P) || m) * G</code>.

A '''bare-key spend''' is a key-path spend of a bare-key output. Because no tweak was applied, the spender cannot produce an internal key <code>P</code> that reconstructs <code>Q</code> via the tweak formula.

====Rationale for disabling====

Bare-key spending is disabled after activation for the following reasons:

# '''It undermines the security model.''' The entire purpose of this BIP is to require disclosure and verification of the internal key via the taproot tweak. Bare-key outputs bypass this mechanism entirely, making the NUMS ban unenforceable. Any exception for bare-key outputs creates an escape hatch that undermines both this BIP and [[bip-0369.mediawiki|BIP 369]].
# '''BIP 341 recommends against it.''' The Taproot specification explicitly states: ''"the output key should commit to an unspendable script path instead of having no script path."'' Bare-key outputs are a deviation from the standard.
# '''Standard wallets do not create them.''' All major wallet implementations apply the taproot tweak when constructing outputs. Bare-key Taproot UTXOs in practice are expected to be negligible.
# '''The BIP 9 signaling period provides migration time.''' Between the start of miner signaling and the activation height, there are months of advance notice for any bare-key holders to move their funds.
# '''Bare-key spending can be reinstated.''' If a future need arises, a subsequent BIP can define a mechanism for bare-key spending (for example, requiring a BIP-32 derivation path as proof of key origin, or another preimage-based verification). Disabling now does not permanently confiscate funds — it defers the problem to a purpose-built solution rather than weakening this BIP with a complex exception.

==Specification==

===Annex format for internal key disclosure===

Post-activation, all witness version 1 key-path spends must include an annex carrying the internal public key using type byte <code>0x02</code>:

<source>
0x50 || 0x02 || P                          (no script tree: 34 bytes total)
0x50 || 0x02 || P || merkle_root           (with script tree: 66 bytes total)
</source>

Where <code>P</code> is the 32-byte x-only internal public key and <code>merkle_root</code> is the 32-byte Merkle root of the script tree. No parity byte is needed: the verifier computes the tweaked key from <code>P</code> and compares the x-coordinate directly against the output key <code>Q</code>.

===Key-path spending rules (post-activation)===

Given the output key <code>Q</code> (the 32-byte witness program) and a key-path spend (1 witness element after removing the optional annex):

# If no annex is present, the spend is '''consensus-invalid'''.
# If an annex is present, it '''must''' have type byte <code>0x02</code> and length exactly 34 or 66 bytes. Any other type byte or length is '''consensus-invalid'''. An annex in a key-path spend has exactly one valid purpose: internal key disclosure.
# If the annex is <code>0x50 || 0x02 || P</code> (34 bytes): compute <code>(Q', parity) = CreateTapTweak(P, null)</code> using <code>hash(TapTweak, bytes(P))</code> as the tweak.
# If the annex is <code>0x50 || 0x02 || P || merkle_root</code> (66 bytes): compute <code>(Q', parity) = CreateTapTweak(P, merkle_root)</code> using <code>hash(TapTweak, bytes(P) || merkle_root)</code> as the tweak.
# If <code>Q' != Q</code> (comparing x-coordinates), the spend is '''consensus-invalid'''. The provided internal key does not match the output key.
# If <code>P</code> matches any entry in the '''banned NUMS points''' list, the spend is '''consensus-invalid'''. This prevents a quantum adversary from key-path spending outputs constructed with a known unspendable internal key.
# Verify the Schnorr signature against <code>Q</code> as in [[bip-0341.mediawiki|BIP 341]]. The spend is valid.

====Pseudocode: Key-path annex parsing====

<source>
def ParseKeypathAnnex(annex):
    if annex[0] != 0x50: return error
    if len(annex) < 2: return error
    if annex[1] != 0x02: return error(BAD_ANNEX_FORMAT)
    if len(annex) != 34 and len(annex) != 66: return error(BAD_ANNEX_FORMAT)
    P = annex[2:34]   // 32-byte x-only internal public key
    if len(annex) == 66:
        merkle_root = annex[34:66]
    else:
        merkle_root = null
    return (P, merkle_root)
</source>

====Pseudocode: Key-path verification====

<source>
def VerifyKeypathHardening(Q, annex_present, annex, flags):
    if not (flags & KEYPATH_HARDENING):
        return OK   // pre-activation: no enforcement

    if not annex_present:
        return error(MISSING_ANNEX)

    (P, merkle_root) = ParseKeypathAnnex(annex)

    // Check banned NUMS points
    if P in BANNED_NUMS_LIST:
        return error(NUMS_BANNED)

    // Verify tweak: compute Q' from P, compare against Q
    (Q', parity) = CreateTapTweak(P, merkle_root)
    if Q' is null:
        return error(TWEAK_MISMATCH)   // invalid pubkey
    if Q'.x != Q.x:
        return error(TWEAK_MISMATCH)

    return OK   // proceed to Schnorr signature verification
</source>

===Banned NUMS points===

The following x-only public keys are banned as internal keys for key-path spends. These are well-known "Nothing Up My Sleeve" points whose discrete logarithms are unknown under classical computation but recoverable by a quantum adversary.

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Name !! X-coordinate (hex) !! Construction
|-
| BIP 341 NUMS (H) || <code>50929b74c1a04954b78b4b6035e97a5e078a5a0f28ec96d547bfee9ace803ac0</code> || <code>lift_x(SHA-256(uncompressed_encoding(G)))</code>, where G is the secp256k1 generator. Defined in [[bip-0341.mediawiki|BIP 341]].
|}

This list may be extended by future soft forks if additional NUMS constructions become widely adopted. Only points with '''publicly known constructions''' are banned — a point is dangerous precisely because any quantum adversary can target it knowing only the construction recipe.

'''Note on randomized NUMS (H + rG):''' [[bip-0341.mediawiki|BIP 341]] recommends using <code>H + rG</code> for privacy. Randomized variants are '''not''' banned because each has a unique private key that only the creator knows. A quantum attacker must solve ECDLP for each <code>H + rG</code> individually, which is no different from attacking any other public key. Users of randomized NUMS who want quantum protection should migrate to outputs using the exact <code>H</code> point (which is banned from key-path spending, forcing script-path use).

