===Activation semantics===

Upon activation at height H:

* All witness version 1 key-path spends '''must''' include an annex with type byte <code>0x02</code> and length 34 or 66 bytes containing the internal public key.
* Key-path spends without an annex are '''consensus-invalid'''. This disables bare-key spending.
* Key-path spends with an annex of any type byte other than <code>0x02</code>, or wrong length, are '''consensus-invalid'''.
* Key-path spends where the provided internal key does not reconstruct the output key via the taproot tweak are '''consensus-invalid'''.
* Key-path spends where the verified internal key matches any banned NUMS point are '''consensus-invalid'''.

==Backward Compatibility==

This proposal is a soft fork. It tightens the rules for witness version 1 key-path spending: transactions valid under the new rules are a subset of transactions valid under the old rules.

Non-upgraded nodes ignore the annex contents (the annex is stripped before validation per [[bip-0341.mediawiki|BIP 341]]), so the augmented witness is transparent to them. The additional annex data (34 or 66 bytes) increases transaction weight slightly but does not affect non-upgraded validation.

Existing Taproot outputs:
* '''Tweaked outputs''' (the vast majority): Key-path spend by including <code>P</code> in the annex. Immediate, no restrictions.
* '''Bare-key outputs''' (rare, not recommended by BIP 341): '''No longer spendable via key-path''' after activation. Holders must migrate funds before activation. The BIP 9 signaling period provides advance notice.

==Security Considerations==

===SHA-256 preimage resistance===

The security of the NUMS ban relies on SHA-256 preimage resistance, not ECDLP hardness. The taproot tweak <code>hash(TapTweak, bytes(P) || ...)</code> binds <code>P</code> to <code>Q</code>. Finding a <code>P' != P</code> that produces the same <code>Q</code> requires finding a preimage of the tagged hash, which has 128-bit quantum security under Grover's algorithm.

===Randomized NUMS points (H + rG)===

[[bip-0341.mediawiki|BIP 341]] recommends using <code>H + rG</code> (randomized NUMS) for privacy. These randomized variants are '''not''' in the banned NUMS list because:

* Each <code>H + rG</code> has a unique discrete logarithm. A quantum attacker must solve ECDLP for each one individually — no shortcut from knowing <code>H</code>'s construction.
* The owner knows <code>r</code> and can key-path spend by revealing <code>P = H + rG</code>, which passes the NUMS check.
* Banning all possible <code>H + rG</code> values is computationally infeasible (the set is the entire curve).

Users who used randomized NUMS and want quantum protection should migrate to new outputs using the '''exact''' <code>H</code> point as internal key (which forces script-path spending).

===Bare-key output impact===

Bare-key outputs (constructed without a taproot tweak) become unspendable via key-path after activation. This is an intentional trade-off:

* [[bip-0341.mediawiki|BIP 341]] explicitly recommends against bare-key outputs.
* All standard wallet implementations apply the tweak.
* Bare-key outputs undermine the entire security model of this BIP and [[bip-0369.mediawiki|BIP 369]]: without internal key verification, the NUMS ban is unenforceable.
* The BIP 9 signaling period provides months of advance notice for migration.
* Bare-key spending may be reinstated by a future BIP if needed, for example by requiring a BIP-32 derivation proof or other key-origin preimage.

===Interaction with BIP 369===

When deployed alongside [[bip-0369.mediawiki|BIP 369]], the combined protections are:

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Output type !! Key-path !! Script-path !! Quantum protection
|-
| NUMS + SPHINCS+ leaf || Banned (NUMS) || SPHINCS+ enforced || Full
|-
| Normal key + SPHINCS+ leaf || Allowed (P revealed) || SPHINCS+ enforced || Script-path only
|-
| Normal key, no SPHINCS+ || Allowed (P revealed) || Schnorr only || None (quantum-vulnerable)
|-
| Bare key || Disabled || N/A (no script tree) || Migrate before activation
|}

